Failed US-Iran talks have spiked oil (Strait of Hormuz risks), adding energy cost pressure", "id_str": "2043471088588362216", "in_reply_to_screen_name": "Ya_sharm", "in_reply_to_status_id_str": "2043470982627856456", "in_reply_to_user_id_str": "1672899780295692289", "is_quote_status": false, "lang": "en", "quote_count": 0, "reply_count": 1, "retweet_count": 0, "retweeted": false, "user_id_str": "1720665183188922368"}, "note_tweet": {"is_expandable": true, "note_tweet_results": {"result": {"entity_set": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [{"indices": [86, 91], "text": "LWLG"}, {"indices": [121, 126], "text": "OPTX"}], "urls": [], "user_mentions": []}, "id": "Tm90ZVR3ZWV0OjIwNDM0NzEwODg1MDg2MDg1MTI=", "text": "The photonics/optics sector (high-speed data comms, AI infrastructure) for names like $LWLG (electro-optic polymers) and $OPTX (components for comms/defense) is tied to tech capex cycles.

Failed US-Iran talks have spiked oil (Strait of Hormuz risks), adding energy cost pressure on data centers and broader risk-off flows that could trigger pullbacks in speculative growth plays.

Fed balance sheet expansion/liquidity injections remain supportive for risk assets, potentially cushioning valuations via easier money—though it risks inflating bubbles in already stretched areas.

Sector macro leans mixed short-term; watch oil and Fed signals for direction. NFA."}}}, "rest_id": "2043471088588362216", "source": "<a href="https://x.ai" rel="nofollow">Banners & Ads</a>", "unmention_data": {}, "views": {"count": "661", "state": "EnabledWithCount"}}

text:
@aleabitoreddit The market seems to be in a photonics frenzy this year, and I've been following your posts since February.

Is there no foreseeable cooldown to this trend? 

Also, I get that there's a memory chip shortage, but SNDK is up 2,800% in 1 year. There is enough backlog to justify this?

